# Swift / iOS / macOS Overlay

Apply this rule only to Swift code and iOS/macOS projects.

## SwiftUI declarative model

- Prefer `View` composition over inheritance
- Keep `body` implementations shallow — extract subviews when `body` grows beyond ~20 lines
- Name view structs in PascalCase, preview providers as `<ViewName>_Previews`
- Use `@ViewBuilder` for complex conditional view construction
- Prefer `Group`, `ForEach`, and `LazyVStack`/`LazyHStack` for dynamic content
- Keep views purely declarative — no imperative logic in `body`

## State management discipline

Use the appropriate property wrapper for each role:

| Wrapper | Use when |
|---------|---------|
| `@State` | Local mutable state owned by this view |
| `@Binding` | Mutable state passed from a parent |
| `@StateObject` | ObservableObject owned by this view (created here) |
| `@ObservedObject` | ObservableObject passed from a parent |
| `@EnvironmentObject` | Shared object injected through the environment |
| `@Environment` | Reading environment values (color scheme, locale, etc.) |

- Do not reach for `@EnvironmentObject` for everything — prefer explicit dependency injection via `@Binding` or init parameters for tightly scoped state
- In Swift 5.9+ / iOS 17+, prefer `@Observable` (Observation framework) over `ObservableObject` for new code

## Async/await patterns

- Prefer `async/await` over completion handlers for new code
- Launch tasks from view lifecycle with `.task { }` modifier (auto-cancels on disappear)
- Use `Task { }` for imperative task launches; cancel on `onDisappear` when needed
- Prefer `AsyncSequence` / `AsyncStream` over Combine `Publisher` for new async event streams
- Do not block the main actor with synchronous I/O

Combine usage:
- Retain Combine where the project already uses it (do not rip out existing `.sink`/`.assign` chains)
- Prefer `async/await` for new network and async work
- Use `.receive(on: DispatchQueue.main)` before UI-bound sink operations

## Safety rules

- **No force unwrap** (`!`): use `guard let`, `if let`, `??`, or `try?` instead
  - Exception: IBOutlets in UIKit code where the contract guarantees non-nil at use time (document why)
- **No force try** (`try!`) in production paths
- **No force cast** (`as!`) without explicit justification
- Prefer `Result<Success, Failure>` over throwing functions in closures and async boundaries

## Xcode project structure

Follow the project's established structure. Common conventions:
```
MyApp/
  App/            — App entry point, AppDelegate/SceneDelegate
  Features/       — Feature modules (one folder per feature)
    FeatureName/
      Views/
      ViewModels/
      Models/
  Core/           — Shared utilities, extensions, services
  Resources/      — Assets, Localizable.strings, Info.plist
```

- Group files by feature, not by type (prefer `Feature/Views/` over `Views/Feature/`)
- Use Swift packages (SPM) for internal modules when the project does so

## Swift Package Manager (SPM)

- Declare dependencies in `Package.swift` — do not mix SPM and CocoaPods without strong reason
- Pin to exact versions or minor ranges for dependencies: `from: "1.2.3"` or `.upToNextMinor(from: "1.2.0")`
- Prefer SPM over CocoaPods or Carthage for new dependencies

## Naming conventions

- Types and protocols: `PascalCase`
- Variables, functions, cases: `camelCase`
- Constants: `camelCase` (Swift convention) — avoid `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`
- Files: match the primary type defined in the file (one primary type per file preferred)
- Protocol names: noun (`Identifiable`) or adjective (`Equatable`), not verb unless a delegate (`DataSourceDelegate`)

## Performance awareness

- Avoid heavy computation in `body` — extract to `@State`/`@StateObject` or use `.onChange`
- Prefer `LazyVStack`/`LazyHStack`/`LazyVGrid` for long scrollable lists
- Minimize `@EnvironmentObject` reads in frequently re-rendered views
- Profile with Instruments (Time Profiler, SwiftUI instrument) before optimizing

## Preview providers

- Provide at least one preview per non-trivial view
- Use `PreviewProvider` (< iOS 17) or `#Preview` macro (iOS 17+)
- Supply representative mock data — avoid empty states as the only preview
- Use `previewLayout(.sizeThatFits)` for component previews

## Testing

- Unit test ViewModels and business logic (not SwiftUI views directly)
- Use `XCTest` for unit tests
- Prefer `XCUITest` for critical UI flows, not as a substitute for unit tests
- Use Swift Testing (`@Test`, `#expect`) for new test code in Swift 5.9+

## Error handling

- Propagate errors with `throws` rather than silently returning `nil`
- Use typed errors (`enum AppError: Error`) for domain errors exposed to callers
- Map networking errors at the boundary — do not leak `URLError` into ViewModels
